label.value: abnormal horsetail-astral microtubule organization

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the horsetail-astral microtubule array is abnormal.

label.value: decreased protein localization to meiotic spindle pole body during prophase I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the meiotic spindle pole body is decreased during prophase of the first meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal histone demethylase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a histone demethylase activity is abnormal.

label.value: abolished histone demethylase activity (H3-K9 specific)

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which H3-K9 specific histone demethylase activity is absent.

label.value: decreased protein localization to chromatin at promoter

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at one or more specific promoter elements is decreased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein localization to chromatin at promoter

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at one or more specific promoter elements is increased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased histone H3-K9 trimethylation at promoter during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the trimethylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 in one or more promoter regions occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: increased histone H3-K9 trimethylation at subtelomeric heterochromatin during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the trimethylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 at subtelomeric regions occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: increased histone H3-K9 trimethylation at silent mating-type cassette during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the trimethylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 in silent mating-type cassettes occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: cell cycle arrest at mitotic G2/M phase transition in absence of mitotic DNA replication checkpoint

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which progression through the mitotic cell cycle is abnormally arrested at the mitotic G2/M phase transition in the absence of the mitotic DNA replication checkpoint. The previous S phase is completed, no replication intermediates can be observed, and cells do not undergo rereplication.

label.value: normal mitosis following cell cycle arrest in response to mitotic DNA replication checkpoint

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which a cell undergoes normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) mitosis upon release from a following release from a G2/M cell cycle block imposed by activation of the mitotic DNA replication checkpoint.

label.value: abnormal chromosome III morphology

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure chromosome III is abnormal.

label.value: increased rDNA copy number during vegetative growth

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of ribosomal DNA (rDNA) repeats present in the rDNA arrays on chromosome III is significantly greater than the range in wild type cells.

label.value: sensitive to manumycin A

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to manumycin A. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of manumycin A that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: decreased RNA stability during cellular response to oxidative stress

value.value: A cell phenotype in which RNA stability is decreased during a cellular response to oxidative stress. RNA molecules are more likely to degrade over a given time period than in wild type. Total RNA or a specific RNA, such as the mRNA transcribed from a gene of interest, may be affected.

label.value: decreased DNA volume

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which DNA occupies a smaller portion of the total nuclear volume than normal. The nuclear volume itself may be normal.

label.value: increased chromatin mobility

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromatin moves within the nucleus to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: increased transcription-induced DNA damage

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of DNA damage occurring as a side effect of transcription in a cell is greater than normal. The number, extent, or both of damage sites may be increased.

label.value: normal DNA volume

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which DNA occupies a normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) portion of the total nuclear volume. The nuclear volume itself is also normal.

label.value: normal growth on beta-glucanase

value.value: A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing  one or more enzymes that degrades cell wall polysaccharides by hydrolyzing beta-glucan linkages.

label.value: resistance to tacrolimus and magnesium chloride

value.value: An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of higher concentrations of tacrolimus and magnesium chloride than normal.

label.value: sensitive to tacrolimus and magnesium chloride

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to a combination of tacrolimus and magnesium chloride. Cells stop growing (and may die) at concentrations of tacrolimus and magnesium chloride that allow wild type cells to grow.

label.value: decreased protein level during cellular response to oxidative stress

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during a cellular response to oxidative stress is lower than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: delayed onset of protein import into nucleus

value.value: A transport phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the import of protein into the nucleus begins later than normal. Import of all proteins or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased ribosome binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of ribosome binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is decreased. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: increased protein phosphorylation during cellular response to salt stress

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, occurs to a greater extent than normal during a cellular response to salt stress.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein localization to cell tip during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the cell tip is increased when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal membrane lipid binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of binding to a lipid in a membrane by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal histone H3-K9 dimethylation at heterochromatin island during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the dimethylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 at heterochromatin islands is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abolished histone H3-K9 dimethylation at heterochromatin island at meiotic gene during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which dimethylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 does not occur at heterochromatin islands near genes that are normally expressed during the meiotic cell cycle.

label.value: decreased histone H3-K9 dimethylation at heterochromatin island at meiotic gene during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which dimethylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 is decreased at heterochromatin islands near genes that are normally expressed during the meiotic cell cycle.

label.value: decreased replication fork colocalization with nuclear pore complex

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which arrested replication forks do not colocalize with nuclear pore complexes (NPCs) longer than actively replicating forks. Normally, arrested replication forks relocate to NPCs as part of replication fork processing, and remain anchored at NPCs while recombination-dependent replication takes place.

label.value: normal replication fork colocalization with nuclear pore complex

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which arrested replication forks colocalize normally (i.e. indistinguishably from wild type) with nuclear pore complexes (NPCs). Normally, arrested replication forks relocate to NPCs as part of replication fork processing, and remain anchored at NPCs while recombination-dependent replication takes place.

label.value: increased phosphorylation of RNA polymerase II C-terminal domain threonine 4 residues during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of the threonine residue at position 4 the C-terminal domain of RNA polymerase II occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: normal phosphorylation of RNA polymerase II C-terminal domain serine 2 residues during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of the serine residue at position 2 within one or more copies of the heptapeptide repeat (YSPTSPS) of the C-terminal domain of RNA polymerase II normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal protein localization to chromatin at RNA polymerase II-transcribed genes during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to regions of chromatin containing genes that can be transcribed by RNA polymerase II is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased replication slippage during replication fork processing

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the increase in small deletions or duplications ("replication slippage") that normally results from processing arrested replication forks is enhanced.

label.value: sensitive to paromomycin

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to paromomycin. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of paromomycin that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: normal phosphorylation of RNA polymerase II C-terminal domain threonine 4 residues during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of the threonine residue at position 4 within one or more copies of the heptapeptide repeat (YSPTSPS) of the C-terminal domain of RNA polymerase II normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal phosphorylation of RNA polymerase II C-terminal domain tyrosine 1 residues during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of the tyrosine residue at position 1 within one or more copies of the heptapeptide repeat (YSPTSPS) of the C-terminal domain of RNA polymerase II normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: viable branched, swollen, elongated, multinucleate, multiseptate vegetative cell

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is viable, branched, has more than one nucleus and more than one septum, and has a larger volume and is longer, than normal. In a swollen cell, both length and diameter may be greater than normal, although the cell is only considered elongated if the length:diameter ratio is also greater than normal.

label.value: normal double-stranded DNA binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of double-stranded DNA binding by a gene product is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The relevant gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: abolished double-stranded DNA binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which double-stranded DNA binding by a gene product does not occur, when a gene or the bound DNA sequence is mutated. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: normal cohesin complex binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to a cohesin complex is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The protein whose binding to the cohesin complex is assayed may be encoded by the mutated gene, or may be encoded by a different gene.

label.value: increased duration of protein localization to mitotic nuclear bridge

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which one or more proteins is localized to the mitotic nuclear bridge for a longer time than normal.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abolished nuclear envelope division

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nuclear envelope division does not occur. Nuclear envelope division takes place at the end of mitosis; the nuclear envelope undergoes localized breakdown in the nuclear bridge midzone and the ends are sealed and retrieved into the envelopes of the separated daughter nuclei. When nuclear envelope division does not occur, the two DNA masses remain linked by the nuclear bridge, and may coalesce back into a single nucleus.

label.value: abnormal nuclear pore localization to mitotic nuclear bridge midzone membrane

value.value: A localization phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nuclear pore localization to the portion of the nuclear envelope enclosing the mitotic nuclear bridge is abnormal, resulting in an abnormal distribution of nuclear pores in the bridge envelope. The nuclear bridge is a narrow constricted region of the nucleus that forms around the mitotic spindle during anaphase. Normally, nuclear pores that lack baskets are found in the midzone of the nuclear bridge.

label.value: abnormal mitotic nuclear bridge midzone membrane domain organization

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which nuclear envelope organization is abnormal in the region of the nuclear envelope that surrounds the mitotic nuclear bridge during mitosis.

label.value: coalescence of partially separated nuclei

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the two DNA masses separated by mitotic anaphase remain linked by the nuclear bridge, and then merge back into a single nucleus.

label.value: increased number of Rad52 foci during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of sites at which the protein Rad52 (also called Rad22) accumulates is greater than normal during a cellular response to hydroxyurea.
